		Comment <a href="#c_1713619512">6</a> by Gideon Marken
		posted on 8/2/2005 at 8:41 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>A similar thing happend to me last year w/ Unreal Tournament. I 'never' play games - and picked this one up. What's funny, is that I quickly learned that the game wasn't just a game - it's a "Development Platform" for 3D games, movies, simulations, anything.</p><p>As a developer - you should do yourself a favor and look under the hood. Both UT2004 and HL2 are great for exploring as development environments. I've spent more time in the Unreal Editor now than in the game - it's amazing - very flexible and a blast to use.</p><p>Are you aware of "Machinia" - I'm sure you are :) Most people have heard of Red vs Blue - but there's a lot more happening in this arena than RvsB. <a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.Machinima.com%3Anmq37NTTe30vOpxDmIxy8B2Bb08&amp;cuid=3321886" rel="nofollow noopener" title="http://www.Machinima.com">http://www.Machinima.com</a></p><p>I went out and bought a game so I could get my mind off of development and instead, I found a new development platform to explore. I've made a few maps - and a music video for one of my songs using Unreal: <a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sonicwallpaper.com%2Fvideo%2Ftheflagchamber.cfm%3AfSwTxlw8mo4uawT1muwD4LocUvM&amp;cuid=3321886" rel="nofollow noopener" title="http://www.sonicwallpaper.com/video/theflagchamber.cfm">http://www.sonicwallpaper.c...</a></p><p>There's so much more that can be done w/ this technology than just 'games.' For example - the "Serious Games Summit" is growing, in addition to "Advergaming" as a market. This points towards new opportunities in software development - maybe not the kind most Web developers get into - but it's going to be a hot area.</p><p>BTW - I still have my ORIGINAL Atari 2600! :)</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
		
